                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3816: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-08T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >June 8, 1934—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 11—6:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>145. Emphasizing the inequitable character of an arms embargo against both
                    parties, the Bolivian representative in a communication to the Secretary General
                    declares that Paraguay’s arsenals at Puerto Sajonia and a munitions factory at
                    Campo Grande specifies in detail the war supplies manufactured in Paraguay and
                    states that Bolivia’s dependence on foreign factories places her in an inferior
                    position.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
